{
  "Which of the following is an element of C^2 (the complex 2-dimensional vector space)?": "",
  "The polynomial x^2 + 1": "",
  "(1, 2, 3)": "",
  "(1 + i, 3 - 2i)": "",
  "The 2x2 identity matrix": "",
  "C^2 consists of ordered pairs of complex numbers. (1+i, 3-2i) is such a pair, making it an element of C^2.": "",
  "What is (2 + 3i)(1 - i)?": "",
  "5 - i": "",
  "-1 + 5i": "",
  "5 + i": "",
  "2 - 3i": "",
  "(2+3i)(1-i) = 2 - 2i + 3i - 3i^2 = 2 + i + 3 = 5 + i.": "",
  "The complex conjugate of z = 3 + 4i is:": "",
  "3 + 4i": "",
  "-3 - 4i": "",
  "3 - 4i": "",
  "-3 + 4i": "",
  "The complex conjugate negates the imaginary part: conj(3 + 4i) = 3 - 4i.": "",
  "What is the modulus (absolute value) of z = 3 + 4i?": "",
  "1": "",
  "7": "",
  "25": "",
  "5": "",
  "|z| = sqrt(3^2 + 4^2) = sqrt(9 + 16) = sqrt(25) = 5.": "",
  "Over the complex numbers, every polynomial of degree n has exactly n roots (counted with multiplicity). This is known as:": "",
  "Euler's Formula": "",
  "The Spectral Theorem": "",
  "The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra": "",
  "The Cayley-Hamilton Theorem": "",
  "The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra states that every non-constant polynomial with complex coefficients has at least one complex root, implying it factors completely into n linear factors over C.": "",
  "A real matrix A has eigenvalue 2 + 3i. What other value must also be an eigenvalue of A?": "",
  "-2 + 3i": "",
  "-2 - 3i": "",
  "3 + 2i": "",
  "Complex eigenvalues of a real matrix always come in conjugate pairs. If 2 + 3i is an eigenvalue, then 2 - 3i must also be an eigenvalue.": "",
  "The conjugate transpose of a complex matrix A (denoted A*) is defined as:": "",
  "A* = A^T only": "",
  "A* = A^(-1)": "",
  "A* = -A^T": "",
  "A* = (conj(A))^T = conj(A^T)": "",
  "The conjugate transpose (or Hermitian conjugate) A* is obtained by transposing A and taking the complex conjugate of every entry. For real matrices, A* = A^T.": "",
  "In C^2, the standard inner product of u = (1, i) and v = (i, 1) is <u, v> = conj(u1)*v1 + conj(u2)*v2. What is <u, v>?": "",
  "2": "",
  "0": "",
  "2i": "",
  "-2i": "",
  "<u,v> = conj(1)*i + conj(i)*1 = 1*i + (-i)*1 = i - i = 0. The vectors u and v are orthogonal in C^2.": "",
  "The dimension of C^n as a complex vector space is n. What is its dimension as a real vector space?": "",
  "n": "",
  "2n": "",
  "n^2": "",
  "n/2": "",
  "Each complex dimension has two real degrees of freedom (real and imaginary parts). So C^n viewed as a real vector space has dimension 2n.": "",
  "The matrix [[0, -1], [1, 0]] represents a 90-degree rotation over the reals. Over the complex numbers, its eigenvalues are:": "",
  "1 and -1": "",
  "i and -i": "",
  "0 and 0": "",
  "1 and i": "",
  "det(A - lambda*I) = lambda^2 + 1 = 0, giving lambda = i and lambda = -i. Over the reals this has no roots, but over C it factors completely.": "",
  "What is a 'complex vector space'?": "",
  "A vector space where the scalars are complex numbers rather than real numbers": "",
  "A vector space that is difficult to understand": "",
  "A vector space with more than 3 dimensions": "",
  "A vector space where all vectors have complex entries but scalars are real": "",
  "A complex vector space is a vector space over the field C of complex numbers. The key distinction from a real vector space is that scalar multiplication is by complex numbers, not just real numbers.": "",
  "What does 'complexification' of a real vector space mean?": "",
  "Making the vector space more complicated": "",
  "Extending a real vector space to allow complex scalars, forming V_C = V + iV": "",
  "Adding more dimensions to the real vector space": "",
  "Computing the complex eigenvalues of every matrix": "",
  "Complexification extends a real vector space V to V_C by allowing complex coefficients: every element has the form u + iv where u, v are in V. If V has real dimension n, then V_C has complex dimension n.": "",
  "What is a 'Hermitian matrix'?": "",
  "Any complex matrix": "",
  "A complex square matrix equal to its own conjugate transpose: A = A*": "",
  "A real symmetric matrix only": "",
  "A matrix named after Charles Hermite that has all zero entries": "",
  "A Hermitian matrix satisfies A = A* (its conjugate transpose). It is the complex generalization of a real symmetric matrix and always has real eigenvalues and orthogonal eigenvectors.": "",
  "What is a 'skew-Hermitian' matrix?": "",
  "A matrix with purely real eigenvalues": "",
  "A matrix satisfying A* = -A": "",
  "An asymmetric real matrix": "",
  "A matrix satisfying A* = A": "",
  "A skew-Hermitian matrix satisfies A* = -A. Its eigenvalues are purely imaginary (or zero). It is the complex analog of a real skew-symmetric matrix.": "",
  "What is 'Euler's formula' and how does it relate to complex vector spaces?": "",
  "e^{i*theta} = cos(theta) + i*sin(theta), connecting complex exponentials to rotations": "",
  "e^x = sum of x^n/n!, the Taylor series for e^x": "",
  "i^2 = -1, the definition of the imaginary unit": "",
  "V + E - F = 2, relating vertices, edges, and faces of polyhedra": "",
  "Euler's formula e^{i*theta} = cos(theta) + i*sin(theta) shows that complex exponentials represent rotations on the unit circle. It is fundamental for understanding eigenvalues of rotation matrices and oscillatory systems.": "",
  "What is the 'spectral theorem for normal matrices'?": "",
  "Only Hermitian matrices can be diagonalized": "",
  "Every matrix has real eigenvalues": "",
  "Every normal matrix (AA* = A*A) is unitarily diagonalizable": "",
  "Every complex matrix is upper triangular": "",
  "A normal matrix commutes with its conjugate transpose. The spectral theorem states that every normal matrix can be diagonalized by a unitary matrix: A = UDU*, where U is unitary and D is diagonal.": "",
  "What is 'Schur's decomposition theorem'?": "",
  "Every matrix over C is diagonalizable": "",
  "Every square complex matrix can be written as A = UTU* where U is unitary and T is upper triangular": "",
  "Every matrix has a unique eigendecomposition": "",
  "The Schur complement is always positive definite": "",
  "Schur's theorem guarantees that any square complex matrix can be unitarily triangularized: A = UTU* with U unitary and T upper triangular. The diagonal of T contains the eigenvalues of A.": "",
  "What is a 'normal matrix'?": "",
  "A matrix with all entries between 0 and 1": "",
  "A matrix that commutes with its conjugate transpose: AA* = A*A": "",
  "A normalized matrix with unit Frobenius norm": "",
  "A matrix with no special properties": "",
  "A normal matrix satisfies AA* = A*A. This class includes Hermitian (A* = A), skew-Hermitian (A* = -A), unitary (A*A = I), and diagonal matrices. All normal matrices are unitarily diagonalizable.": "",
  "What does 'algebraically closed' mean for the complex numbers C?": "",
  "Every complex number has a multiplicative inverse": "",
  "The set of complex numbers is finite": "",
  "Every non-constant polynomial with complex coefficients has at least one complex root": "",
  "Complex addition is commutative": "",
  "C is algebraically closed: every polynomial equation of degree >= 1 has a solution in C. This is why the characteristic polynomial always fully factors over C, guaranteeing n eigenvalues (with multiplicity) for an n x n matrix.": "",
  "What is the 'polar form' of a complex number?": "",
  "z = a + bi where a and b are real under normal circumstances": "",
  "z = conj(z) for all z, particularly regarding polar in most standard conditions": "",
  "z = r * e^{i*theta} = r(cos(theta) + i*sin(theta)) where r = |z| and theta is the argument": "",
  "z = (x, y) as a point in R^2 within the typical range of values": "",
  "The polar form expresses a complex number using its modulus r = |z| and argument theta: z = r*e^{i*theta}. This representation makes multiplication easy (multiply moduli, add arguments) and reveals rotational structure.": "",
  "An electrical engineer models an AC circuit with impedance matrix Z with complex entries. The impedance of a component is z = 3 + 4i ohms. What is the magnitude of this impedance?": "",
  "5 ohms": "",
  "7 ohms": "",
  "25 ohms": "",
  "1 ohm": "",
  "|z| = sqrt(3^2 + 4^2) = sqrt(25) = 5 ohms. The modulus of the complex impedance gives the total impedance magnitude affecting current flow.": "",
  "A control systems engineer finds that a system has transfer function poles at -1 + 2i and -1 - 2i. Is the system stable?": "",
  "Stability cannot be determined from poles alone": "",
  "No, because the poles are complex": "",
  "No, because the imaginary parts are nonzero": "",
  "Yes, because both poles have negative real parts": "",
  "A linear system is stable if all poles have negative real parts (lie in the left half-plane). Both poles have real part -1 < 0, so the system is stable. The imaginary parts cause oscillations that decay over time.": "",
  "A quantum physicist works with the Hermitian matrix A = [[2, 1-i], [1+i, 3]]. She verifies it is Hermitian by checking A = A*. What is the (2,1) entry of A*?": "",
  "1 - i": "",
  "1 + i": "",
  "-1 + i": "",
  "A* is the conjugate transpose. The (2,1) entry of A* = conj(A(1,2)) = conj(1-i) = 1+i. Since this equals A(2,1) = 1+i, the matrix is indeed Hermitian.": "",
  "A signal processing researcher expresses a complex sinusoid as e^{i*2*pi*f*t}. Using Euler's formula, what are the real and imaginary parts?": "",
  "Real: 2*pi*f, Imaginary: t": "",
  "Real: cos(2*pi*f*t), Imaginary: sin(2*pi*f*t)": "",
  "Real: e^{2*pi*f}, Imaginary: i*t": "",
  "Real: sin(2*pi*f*t), Imaginary: cos(2*pi*f*t)": "",
  "By Euler's formula, e^{i*theta} = cos(theta) + i*sin(theta). With theta = 2*pi*f*t, the real part is cos(2*pi*f*t) and the imaginary part is sin(2*pi*f*t).": "",
  "A vibration engineer finds that a system's complex eigenvalues are -0.5 + 3i and -0.5 - 3i. The oscillation frequency is determined by the imaginary part. What is the frequency in radians per second?": "",
  "3 rad/s": "",
  "0.5 rad/s": "",
  "3.5 rad/s": "",
  "6 rad/s": "",
  "For complex eigenvalues a +/- bi, the oscillation frequency is |b| = 3 rad/s, and the decay rate is |a| = 0.5 per second. The system oscillates at 3 rad/s while exponentially decaying.": "",
  "A data scientist encounters a real 3x3 matrix with eigenvalues 2, 1+i, and 1-i. She verifies the characteristic polynomial has degree 3 with real coefficients. What is the product of all eigenvalues (which equals the determinant)?": "",
  "2 + 2i": "",
  "6": "",
  "4": "",
  "det(A) = product of eigenvalues = 2 * (1+i) * (1-i) = 2 * (1 + 1) = 2 * 2 = 4. The conjugate pair product (1+i)(1-i) = 1 - i^2 = 2 is real, so the determinant is real as expected.": "",
  "A telecommunications engineer uses the DFT (Discrete Fourier Transform) matrix F_4, a 4x4 complex matrix. The entries involve omega = e^{2*pi*i/4} = i. What is omega^2?": "",
  "i": "",
  "-1": "",
  "-i": "",
  "omega = e^{2*pi*i/4} = e^{i*pi/2} = i. So omega^2 = i^2 = -1.": "",
  "A robotics researcher uses rotation matrices in 3D. A rotation by angle theta about the z-axis has eigenvalues 1, e^{i*theta}, and e^{-i*theta}. For theta = pi/2, what are the eigenvalues?": "",
  "1, i, -i": "",
  "1, 1, -1": "",
  "1, 0, 0": "",
  "i, -i, -1": "",
  "For theta = pi/2: e^{i*pi/2} = cos(pi/2) + i*sin(pi/2) = i, and e^{-i*pi/2} = -i. So the eigenvalues are 1, i, -i.": "",
  "A cryptographer uses complex roots of unity in number-theoretic computations. The 3rd roots of unity are solutions to z^3 = 1. How many complex roots are there?": "",
  "3": "",
  "z^3 = 1 has exactly 3 roots (by the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra): z = 1, z = e^{2*pi*i/3}, and z = e^{4*pi*i/3}. These are equally spaced on the unit circle.": "",
  "A physicist studying oscillatory systems writes the general solution as x(t) = Re(c * e^{(a+bi)t}) where a + bi is a complex eigenvalue. If a = -1 and b = 2, describe the behavior of x(t).": "",
  "Exponentially decaying oscillation with decay rate 1 and frequency 2": "",
  "Exponentially growing oscillation": "",
  "Purely exponential decay without oscillation": "",
  "Constant amplitude oscillation": "",
  "x(t) = Re(c * e^{(-1+2i)t}) = Re(c * e^{-t} * e^{2it}). The e^{-t} factor causes exponential decay (rate 1) while e^{2it} = cos(2t) + i*sin(2t) produces oscillation at frequency 2 rad/s.": ""
